## Fiscal Impact and Tax Contributions

### 1. Tax Payments Exceed Public Service Costs

Contrary to popular belief, illegal immigrants contribute more in taxes than they consume in public services. Professor Francine Lipman notes that unauthorized immigrants pay into Social Security, Medicare, and unemployment insurance programs without being eligible for most benefits, resulting in a net positive fiscal impact ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_impact_of_illegal_immigrants_in_the_United_States)).

A Congressional Budget Office (CBO) review found that over the long term, tax revenues generated by immigrants—both legal and unauthorized—exceed the cost of services they use ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_impact_of_illegal_immigrants_in_the_United_States)).

### 2. Contributions to Social Security and Medicare

Illegal immigrants often pay payroll taxes using Individual Taxpayer Identification Numbers (ITINs) or false Social Security numbers, contributing billions annually to Social Security and Medicare funds. These contributions help sustain these programs, especially as the native-born population ages ([New York Times, 2005](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_impact_of_illegal_immigrants_in_the_United_States)).

---

## Labor Market Effects

### 1. Impact on Wages and Employment

While some economists, such as Jorge Borjas, argue that illegal immigration may reduce wages for certain low-skilled groups (e.g., high school dropouts), the overall effect on the average American is positive or neutral. Borjas himself acknowledges that the average American's wealth has increased by approximately 1% due to illegal immigration ([The Hill, 2014](https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/foreign-policy/203984-illegal-immigrants-benefit-the-us-economy)).

Furthermore, many studies find no significant detrimental effects on employment opportunities or wages for native-born workers. Immigration tends to complement rather than substitute native labor, especially in different skill segments ([StudentShare, 2024](https://studentshare.org/sociology/1458641-positive-and-negative-aspects-of-immigration-in-the-united-states)).

### 2. Supporting American Jobs and Economic Stability

Illegal immigrants contribute to the creation of approximately 8 million U.S. jobs through their economic activities, including consumption and labor participation ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_impact_of_illegal_immigrants_in_the_United_States)). Their work in construction, landscaping, plumbing, and other essential services supports industries that employ millions of Americans.

---

## Social and Cultural Contributions

### 1. Enhancing Cultural Diversity and Innovation

Immigration enriches American culture by introducing diverse languages, traditions, and ideas. This diversity fosters creativity and innovation, which are critical for economic competitiveness in a globalized world ([Mic, 2014](https://www.mic.com/articles/28614/3-ways-immigrants-are-helping-american-culture-and-business-soar)).

### 2. Family Unity and Social Integration

Family-based immigration, including undocumented immigrants seeking legalization, promotes family unity and social stability. Legalization pathways would enable undocumented immigrants to integrate more fully into society, contributing to community cohesion and economic security ([FWD.us, 2020](https://www.fwd.us/news/immigration-facts-the-positive-economic-impact-of-immigration)).

---

## Addressing Common Concerns

### 1. Crime Rates and Public Safety

Some argue that illegal immigration increases crime rates. However, empirical evidence does not support this claim conclusively. Many studies show that immigrants, including undocumented ones, commit crimes at lower rates than native-born citizens ([The Hill, 2014](https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/foreign-policy/203984-illegal-immigrants-benefit-the-us-economy)).

### 2. Use of Public Services

Although unauthorized immigrants do use some public services, especially in health care and education, their overall use is lower than that of native-born households. They often avoid public services due to fear of deportation and legal restrictions ([Wikipedia, 2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_impact_of_illegal_immigrants_in_the_United_States)).

